node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.text: Photo by @martinedstrom / Climbers Pete Athans (@mreverest7x) and Dawa Yangzum Sherpa (@dawayangzum) making their way across the sand plains above Dingboche in Nepal, with a clear view of Ama Dablam in the background. Photographed for Nat Geo as the pair were making their way to Everest Base Camp during the 2019 @insidenatgeo Perpetual Planet expedition. The expedition aimed to find answers to how climate change affects the upper Himalayas and has led to several interesting discoveries since then—including the extraordinary finding of microplastics high up on Mount Everest itself. Follow @martinedstrom for more from this story and the VR episodes we filmed during the expedition. #nepal #expedition #himalayas #onassignment

node.text: Photo by @ming.t.poon / @ianmcintosh and @sage_cattabriga_alosa climbing a couloir in the Lofoten Islands of Norway. Of all the places I've been for sliding on snow, Lofoten might be the most beautiful. Stacked with couloirs and other terrain right above the sea, it's a dreamland for skiers and snowboarders. Refuel with cod, rejuvenate with a sauna, relax with the aurora borealis and repeat.

node.text: Photo by @martinedstrom / A candid moment as Dawa Yangzum Sherpa (@dawayangzum) lights incense in the Pangboche Monastery in the Khumbu Valley, Nepal. As high-altitude climbing in the Himalayas has developed mostly thanks to the Sherpa people who have lived underneath these big mountains for centuries, many Buddhist ceremonies have been incorporated. Before big expeditions, climbers often take part in a "puja" ceremony, where a local Buddhist monk ushers good fortune on them. Dawa is one of Nepal's foremost climbers and was part of the summit team on the 2019 @insidenatgeo Perpetual Planet expedition to Mount Everest. I photographed this image while on assignment to document it in VR. You can find the 360° videos on the Nat Geo YouTube channel. Follow @martinedstrom for more from Nepal and in VR. #Nepal #NatGeoVR #Everest
